                         (c) 1991 by Brian S. Minsker



    RINGS was written in Borland's TurboBASIC.  CGA, EGA, VGA, and MCGA
    color and monochrome systems are supported, with autodetection of 
    the video adapter standard, and command line options to allow the
    user to select other video modes (or if the program is unable to
    determine the type of monitor attached to the system).

    To run RINGS, simply type:

                            RINGS <video display>

    The video display parameter is generally not required.  RINGS should
    be able to detect the type of display used by your system and set its
    parameters accordingly.  If for some reason RINGS cannot detect your
    display, you will need to use the video display parameter in the 
    command line.  The following parameters may be used (either upper or
    lower case is fine):

         C  = CGA display
         EM = EGA monochrome display
         EC = EGA color display
         VM = VGA monochrome display
         VC = VGA color display
         MM = MCGA monochrome display
         MM = MCGA color display

    Both the MCGA monochrome and color displays show operate as monochrome
    since the 640 x 480 16-color display is not explicitly supported by
    TurboBASIC.  If you have an MCGA color display, you can try to run
    RINGS in VGA color mode.  I would be interested in knowing if the MCGA
    color system is capable of running in VGA color mode.  If so, MCGA
    color support will be included in the next revision of RINGS.

